<p id="d1e2708">Many countries have imposed some kind of lockdown, in which the free movement of people is significantly restricted. Thus, the true contact network 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e2711" display="inline" altimg="si1.svg">
   <mi>G</mi>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> varies over time. We use a time-varying traffic matrix 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e2716" display="inline" altimg="si99.svg">
   <mrow>
    <mi>M</mi>
    <mrow>
     <mo>[</mo>
     <mi>k</mi>
     <mo>]</mo>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> as an approximation for the prior infection matrix 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e2729" display="inline" altimg="si100.svg">
   <mrow>
    <msub>
     <mrow>
      <mi>B</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow>
      <mtext>prior</mtext>
     </mrow>
    </msub>
    <mrow>
     <mo>[</mo>
     <mi>k</mi>
     <mo>]</mo>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>, whose entries equal 
 <disp-formula id="fd8">
  <label>(8)</label>
  <math id="d1e2754" display="block" altimg="si101.svg">
   <mrow>
    <msub>
     <mrow>
      <mi>B</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow>
      <mtext>prior</mtext>
     </mrow>
    </msub>
    <mrow>
     <mo>[</mo>
     <mi>k</mi>
     <mo>]</mo>
    </mrow>
    <mo linebreak="goodbreak">=</mo>
    <mo class="qopname">diag</mo>
    <mfenced open="(" close=")">
     <mrow>
      <msub>
       <mrow>
        <mi>c</mi>
       </mrow>
       <mrow>
        <mn>1</mn>
       </mrow>
      </msub>
      <mo>,</mo>
      <mo>…</mo>
      <mo>,</mo>
      <msub>
       <mrow>
        <mi>c</mi>
       </mrow>
       <mrow>
        <mi>N</mi>
       </mrow>
      </msub>
     </mrow>
    </mfenced>
    <mi>M</mi>
    <mrow>
     <mo>[</mo>
     <mi>k</mi>
     <mo>]</mo>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </disp-formula>for all times 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e2807" display="inline" altimg="si140.svg">
   <mi>k</mi>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>. The positive scalars 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e2812" display="inline" altimg="si84.svg">
   <mrow>
    <msub>
     <mrow>
      <mi>c</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow>
      <mn>1</mn>
     </mrow>
    </msub>
    <mo>,</mo>
    <mo>…</mo>
    <mo>,</mo>
    <msub>
     <mrow>
      <mi>c</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow>
      <mi>N</mi>
     </mrow>
    </msub>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> are unknown and are set by hold-out validation. We propose a Bayesian approach called 
 <italic>NIPA dynamic prior</italic> to estimate the true infection matrix 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e2840" display="inline" altimg="si104.svg">
   <mrow>
    <mi>B</mi>
    <mrow>
     <mo>[</mo>
     <mi>k</mi>
     <mo>]</mo>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> from the time series of infected cases 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e2853" display="inline" altimg="si138.svg">
   <mrow>
    <msub>
     <mrow>
      <mi>y</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow>
      <mi>i</mi>
     </mrow>
    </msub>
    <mrow>
     <mo>[</mo>
     <mi>k</mi>
     <mo>]</mo>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> and the prior infection matrix 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e2871" display="inline" altimg="si100.svg">
   <mrow>
    <msub>
     <mrow>
      <mi>B</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow>
      <mtext>prior</mtext>
     </mrow>
    </msub>
    <mrow>
     <mo>[</mo>
     <mi>k</mi>
     <mo>]</mo>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>. Using the estimated time-varying infection matrix 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e2889" display="inline" altimg="si107.svg">
   <mrow>
    <msub>
     <mrow>
      <mi>B</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow>
      <mtext>posterior</mtext>
     </mrow>
    </msub>
    <mrow>
     <mo>[</mo>
     <mi>k</mi>
     <mo>]</mo>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> and the curing rates 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e2908" display="inline" altimg="si76.svg">
   <msub>
    <mrow>
     <mi>δ</mi>
    </mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi>i</mi>
    </mrow>
   </msub>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> for each region 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e2918" display="inline" altimg="si137.svg">
   <mi>i</mi>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>, we forecast the outbreak by iterating the SIR model. Appendix D explains the technical details of NIPA dynamic prior.
</p>
